Title: Sensors composition inheritance
Body: Since converted sensors just use some function [float] -> [SensorResult]  compose the sensor out of a function to separate concerns of being a sensor  and converting sensor readings.  This is implemented via templates so that assembly of the sensor occurs at compile time  incurring zero runtime overhead (probably actually an improvement  since a virtual method lookup is no longer involved).    This also opens the possibility for more complex sensor types to use compositions of functions  such as a fuel level sensor that converts volts -> resistance -> liters  using for example a `VoltageDividerConverter` and a `TableLookupConverter` chained together.

Title: add sensor framework tests
Body: Add new sensor framework  plus unit tests.  ~~Not currently consumed anywhere - so no actual function changes to the firmware yet.~~ **Oil pressure sensor logic replaced as a first consumer!**    Features:  - Uniform consumption of sensors  including failure detection  - `SensorReader<T>` provides simple sensor consumption including fallback logic  - Transparent sensor mocking both in tests and at runtime  including via the console  - Sensor results are only computed when new ADC values are read  and cached for later consumption (prevents doing extra work converting the sensor every time)  - Reduces code duplication by decoupling _how_ to convert a sensor from _what_ we're sensing.  Not only does this simplify the code  it reduces the byte size of hot code  putting less stress on the instruction cache and branch predictor.  - Provides framework for sensor redundancy/fallback/compositing: a sensor implementation can read other sensors  and decide what to return based on their values (example: TPS sensor redundancy)  - Adding new sensors is cheap and easy - see comment in `sensor.h`  - Separates implementation from initialization: sensors are implemented in `controllers/sensors/`  and wired up in `init/sensors/`.  This makes it easy to test functionality in an isolated test world.

Title: Improve wall wetting AE to use time constant
Body: Previously  AE used a constant for "amount of fuel sucked from wall in one cycle" when in fact that's not how gasoline works.  There's an amount of gasoline sucked off the wall PER TIME  not PER CYCLE.  This change replaces the per-cycle parameter with a time constant (tau) parameter instead.

Title: Update to Matt s MAF code for VE table tuning
Body: PR-ing this now in the spirit of small changes.   Built upon Matt's last PR to allow the MAF fuelling to be tuned with the VE table.   MAF air charge fuelling now targets AFR and has correction for air flow inconsistencies like reversion through the MAF.   Creates a value for "airChargeLoad" which is a standardised VE value and is used as Y axis for the VE table.   VE table tunes MAF fuel by percentage. 100 = no correction  80 = 20% less fuel  120 = 20% more fuel.   VE table enabled in Tuner studio for LM_REAL_MAF instead of Fuel Table.    Known issues:  Pulse width output is tested ok but does cause the build test to fail due to the change in the maths.  Y axis on VE table does not move in TS  need to change rusefi.input file to solve this for the next PR.   For now the table works but does not show a live highlight/cursor in TS.

Title: simplify getTimeNowNt
Body: While working on #1874  I rewrote `getTimeNowNt` to be much simpler.  On ARM this implementation is actually branch free  so has the potential to be faster.    To answer the deleted comment ` // todo: why is this implementation not used? `:  In a real-time application  I think we prefer a deterministic algorithm  even if it requires a global lock.  A lock free solution has terrible worst case performance  which is what we care most about when realtime.  At -O2  we're only locked for something like 16-18 cycles - only 110 nanoseconds.  It's just not enough time to worry about.

Title: switch to single precision constants
Body: `0.25`: this is a double  `0.25f`: this is a float    Adding this compiler option means these are both actually floats.  We don't have the hardware to process doubles  so it happens instead in software.    For example  the line of code `float instantRpm = (60000000.0 / 360 * US_TO_NT_MULTIPLIER) * angleDiff / time;` compiles to this:    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/96042981-2017b180-0e23-11eb-911a-c9871357c2ac.png)    Circled are SOFTWARE EMULATED `double` math operations.  Bad! Slow! So much extra code!    With this option added  it now compiles to this:    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568254/96043358-afbd6000-0e23-11eb-8c31-ba4c5d7a995a.png)    As a bonus  this saves ~1k of flash space.

Title: Store ini filesystem in compressed block device
Body: This PR converts the ini filesystem from:  ini file -> zip file -> FAT filesystem (ini decompressed by pc)  to  ini file -> FAT filesystem -> gzip (entire filesystem decompressed on the fly  in-ECU)    This means that the filesystem appears to contain an ini file  not an ini.zip file.  With this  you can open the ini *directly from TunerStudio* instead of having to first unzip it to your PC.  As an added bonus  it consumes less flash space - currently about 75k  but presents as a full 1MB filesystem.    Unfortunately  right now it requires 32KB of RAM to store the DEFLATE dictionary  which means it doesn't fit on an F405/7 (but does fit on an F42x/F7/H7).  It may be possible to compress with a smaller dictionary  but I haven't tried yet.

Title: Embed ini
Body: Embed the tunerstudio ini in the firmware - it mounts as a USB mass storage device when you connect the ECU without an SD card.    This works by creating a read-only FAT filesystem embedded in the firmware image  and mounting it as a fake SD card when we don't have an SD card installed.

Title: Openblt
Body: This adds OpenBLT bootloader and tools as submodule to `firmware/ext/`  Also OpenBLT is build if `USE_OPENBLT` set to yes before calling `common_make.sh`  Boards specific OpenBLT code is expected at `firmware/config/boards/<board_name>/openblt/`. See OpenBLT `Target/Demo` or RusEFI's `boards/subaru_eg33` for example.  Initially OpenBLT can be flashed using DFU tool.  To flash main FW DFU util can be used.  Currently CRC check of main application is disabled in OpenBLT (for subaru board) and it is possible to load main application using DFU.  ```  $ time ./BootCommander -t=xcp_can -d=can0 /home/work/rusefi/rusefi/firmware/build/rusefi.srec   --------------------------------------------------------------------------  BootCommander version 1.04.02. Performs firmware updates on a micro-  controller based system that runs the OpenBLT bootloader. Title: Print BSS and RAM4 totals at the end of make
Body: The compiler was outsmarting us: UNUSED_CCM disappeared entirely (probably because of the *0)   while UNUSED_RAM was helpfully moved to read-only flash.  It's possible making these not static  would have helped  but link time optimization might have gotten rid of them too.    Instead  print BSS and RAM4 totals at the end using the java script.  If java is unable to run   don't error out the Makefile  just complain a little and move on.  Until the gcc_map_reader  actually works with RAM4  we print it manually.
